Times are altered at Ostend now of the Britons who go thither , very few look like lords , or act like those members of our hereditary aristocracy . 
They seem for the most part shabby in attire , dingy of linen , lovers of billiards and brandy , and cigars and greasy ordinaries . 
But it may be said as a rule , that every Englishman in the Duke of Wellington's army paid his way . 
The remembrance of such a fact surely becomes a nation of shopkeepers . 
It was a blessing for a commerce loving country to be overrun by such an army of customers and to have such creditable warriors to feed . 
And the country which they came to protect is not military . 
